# Specification Structure Rule

When creating or updating requirement specifications, follow the project specification system exactly.

## Primary location and format

- Business/domain requirement specifications live in `spec/requirements/`.
- Requirement documents in this area must use Markdown `.md`.
- Keep requirement docs prominent in `spec/requirements/` root.
- The overarching spec-system document is `spec/requirements/GEN-Spec-Spezifikation.md`.

## Feature label and file-family convention

- Every feature must define a short label (for example `TPLK`).
- Create exactly one hub file per feature: `<LABEL>-<Feature-Name>.md`.
- Hub heading format: `# Feature [<LABEL>]: <Feature-Name>`.
- Immediately below the hub heading, add a section `## Spezifikationen` and list all child files there.
- Child files under the same feature must use the same label prefix and heading:
 - filename example: `TPLK-Episode-Spezifikation.md`
 - heading format: `# Feature-of [<LABEL>]: <Feature-Name>`
- The hub file child-file list is authoritative for that feature.

## Mandatory hierarchy

Each specification document must use this hierarchy (as headings):

1. Feature
2. Use Case
3. Story
4. Item

Do not skip levels when adding detailed requirements.

## Mandatory label on every level

Each specification file must contain exactly one top heading that is either:
- `# Feature [<LABEL>]: <Feature-Name>` (hub file), or
- `# Feature-of [<LABEL>]: <Feature-Name>` (child file).
Every Use Case, Story, and Item should carry exactly one status label.
Use plain Markdown status tokens in headings (for example `## Use Case: ... [Spec]` and `#### Item: ... [Ready]`).
Do not use a dash before the status marker (write `Title [Ready]`, not `Title - [Ready]`).

Defaulting rule:

- If a Use Case, Story, or Item heading has no status label, assume `Spec` and insert `[Spec]` automatically when editing.
- Never leave Use Case/Story/Item headings unlabeled after an edit.

## Translation hint convention (optional)

- Translation hints are allowed in specification headings using this format: `[<LANG>: <text>]` (for example `[EN: Coordination Protocol]`).
- Place translation hints before the status label in headings.
- Canonical example: `### Story: Koordinationsprotokoll [EN: Coordination Protocol] [Spec]`
- Translation hints do not replace the required status label.

## Semantic hint labels (optional)

- Semantic hint labels are allowed in these formats: `{name}` or `{name1, name2, ...}`.
- Initial recommended labels: `{view}`, `{tab}`, `{panel}`, `{process}`, `{function}`, `{structure}`, `{design}`, `{architecture}`, `{data}`.
- Authors may introduce additional local labels when useful.
- The assistant should interpret labels as contextual guidance, not hard constraints.
- Example interpretation: `{process}` suggests considering the process framework, but does not mandate it.
- Brief label intent:
 - `{view}`: page/view-level behavior
 - `{tab}`: tab-scoped behavior
 - `{panel}`: panel/section-level behavior
 - `{process}`: process/workflow guidance
 - `{function}`: functional behavior or capability
 - `{structure}`: structural decomposition or architecture/layout hints
 - `{design}`: visual design and UX appearance hints
 - `{architecture}`: system/module architecture concerns
 - `{data}`: data-handling semantics and default/core seed-data expectations
- Recommended heading order: `<Title> {label-or-label-list} [<LANG>: <text>] [Status]`.
- Example: `### Story: Koordinationsprotokoll {process} [EN: Coordination Protocol] [Spec]`
- Example with multiple hints: `### Story: Koordinationsprotokoll {design, function} [EN: Coordination Protocol] [Spec]`

## Status hierarchy gate

- A parent level cannot be marked `Done` while any direct or nested lower level is not `Done`.
- Enforce top-down consistency before finishing edits:
 - Use Case `Done` requires all Stories/Items below it to be `Done`.
 - Story `Done` requires all Items below it to be `Done`.
- If any lower level is not `Done`, keep or downgrade the parent to the appropriate non-`Done` state.

## Status assumption policy

- When updating specifications from requirements/discussion, assume starting status `Spec` unless the user explicitly requests another status.
- Exception: when the user asks to reverse-engineer/re-engineer from existing implementation code, use starting status `Impl`.

## TODO discussion marker

- In specification documents, the text label `TODO` is allowed as an inline discussion marker.
- Anything written after `TODO` on the same textual line is treated as not yet decided and still to be discussed.
- If that `TODO` text visually wraps into continuation lines (soft-wrap/paragraph overflow), the wrapped continuation belongs to the same TODO note.
- Use `TODO` for open discussion points only; do not treat it as implemented/committed requirement text.

## Temporary scope delimiters

- In specification files, users may mark a temporary focus region with `>>>>>` (open) and `<<<<<` (close).
- When present, prioritize content inside these delimiters for the requested task.
- Treat these delimiters as temporary working markers, not as part of final requirement content.
- After completing the requested change, remove these delimiters if the task includes marker resolution/cleanup.

Allowed labels only:

- `Spec` (ongoing specification)
- `Ready` (ready for implementation)
- `Impl` (being implemented)
- `QA` (QA test creation outstanding)
- `Done` (fully complete)

## German language requirement

- Specifications under `spec/requirements/` must be written in German.
- Use proper umlauts (`ä`, `ö`, `ü`, `Ä`, `Ö`, `Ü`) and `ß` where linguistically correct.
- Avoid fallback spellings like `ae`, `oe`, `ue` in final German specification wording unless a technical key/name requires ASCII.

## Manual synchronization

- If the specification system/structure changes, update `doc/specification-manual.qmd` in the same change set.
- Keep wording concise and consistent with existing manuals.

